In the past decade , with the successful launch of the soil moisture and ocean salinity ( SMOS ) satellite by the European Space Agency ( ESA ) , the Aquarius/SAC-D satellite , and the soil moisture active passive ( SMAP ) satellite by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration ( NASA ) , global sea surface salinity (
SSS
) observations from space have become possible and a significant improvement has been made to understand the ocean dynamics and climate change .
